{How Purdy Won #6. Dr Cornforth was later a Nobel prize winner for Chemistry.} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 exd6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Bd3 Nc6 $1 {Perhaps Cornforth was counting on the "book" line 7...b6 followed by ...c5 as in Rubinstein,A-Steiner,A/Budapest 1929. It leads to "hanging pawns". The point of playing 7...c6 at once is that it enable Black to play ...Bd6 if hit by a3, as Nb5 is prevented.} 8. Nge2 $1 {More elastic than 8.Nf3.} O-O 9. O-O Bf6 10. b3 Re8 11. Be3 Bg4 $1 12. Qd2 {Had White seen deeper, he would have played Rfc1! first.} Bh5 13. Nf4 Bg6 14. Nxg6 $2 {Overlooking Black's fifteenth, apparently.} hxg6 15. Be4 Rb8 16. Rfe1 (16. g4 {The attack is overwhelming.}) 16... Ne7 17. Bg5 0-1


