{How Purdy Won #5. Hallmann was Australian OTB champion at the time.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. e3 Be7 6. Nf3 O-O 7. Rc1 a6 8. c5 c6 9. b4 a5 10. b5 e5 11. Nd2 Re8 12. Be2 Nf8 13. Qa4 exd4 14. exd4 Ne6 15. Be3 Bxc5 $1 16. bxc6 bxc6 $1 17. dxc5 d4 18. Qxc6 Bd7 19. Qd6 (19. Qb6 Qe7 $1 20. Nde4 dxe3 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. O-O Qd4 $1 $36) 19... dxe3 20. fxe3 Rc8 21. Nce4 Nxe4 22. Nxe4 Qh4+ $1 23. Ng3 Qg5 $3 24. O-O (24. Qxd7 Rcd8 $1 25. Qa4 Qxe3 $44) 24... Qxe3+ 25. Kh1 Bc6 26. Bc4 (26. Ba6 Rc7 {...Rd8-+}) 26... Red8 27. Nf5 (27. Rce1 Qc3 28. Bxe6 (28. Qe7 Rc7 29. Qh4 Rd4) 28... Rxd6 29. Bxf7+ Kh8 30. cxd6 Qd2 $17) 27... Bxg2+ 28. Kxg2 Qe4+ 29. Rf3 Rxd6 30. Nxd6 Qg6+ $1 31. Kf2 $1 (31. Rg3 Qh6) 31... Rxc5 $1 32. Nxf7 Rc7 $1 (32... Rf5 33. Nd8) (32... Rh5 33. Bd3) 33. Nd6 (33. Bxe6 Qxe6 34. Rxc7 Qb6+ $19) (33. Ng5 Rxc4 34. Rxc4 Qxg5 35. Rc8+ Nd8 $19) (33. Ne5 Qh6 34. Bxe6+ Qxe6 35. Rxc7 Qb6+ $19) 33... h5 $1 34. Kf1 {This makes Bxe6+ a real threat. If at once} (34. Bxe6+ Qxe6 35. Rxc7 Qxd6 {and White cannot escape the loss of a second pawn, after which the two rooks will fail to draw, except by} 36. Rff7 Qxh2+ 37. Kf1 Qh3+ 38. Kf2 Qh4+ 39. Kf1 Qg3 $1 40. a4 $1 Kh7 $19 (40... h4 $2 41. Rxg7+ $11)) (34. Re3 Qf6+ 35. Ke1 Qf4 $1 36. Bxe6+ Kf8 37. Rxc7 Qxe3+ $19) (34. Rf5 Rd7 $1 35. Rg1 Qh6 36. Ne4 Rd2+ $1 37. Kf3 Rd3+ $3 38. Kg2 Rd4 $19) 34... Kh7 35. Bd3 Rxc1+ 36. Kf2 Rc2+ $1 37. Kf1 Rxa2 38. Bxg6+ Kxg6 $19 39. Kg1 a4 40. Nc4 Nd4 41. Re3 Kf5 42. Nb6 g5 43. h3 a3 44. Nd5 Nb5 $1 45. Ne7+ Kf6 46. Nd5+ Kf7 47. Rf3+ Ke6 ({After} 47... Ke6 48. Nc3 Nxc3 49. Rxc3 g4 {and the Black king creeps up, using the g-pawn for shelter.}) 0-1


