{How Purdy Won #25. Tim Harding analysed this game without access to Purdy's notes for his book Winning At Correspondence Chess but the book was cut by the publishers so this was omitted. Eventually the notes appeared in Chess Mail 5/ 1998. This game is a fine example of defence turned into counter-attack.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Bg5 h6 5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. Nc3 c6 7. Qb3 Nd7 8. e4 dxe4 9. Nxe4 Qf4 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. Ng3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rad1 Rd8 14. Bb1 Qc7 15. Rfe1 Bd7 16. Ne5 Be8 17. Qc2 g6 18. Qc1 Kg7 19. h4 h5 20. Qe3 Rac8 21. a3 {Black is cramped and under pressure on the kingside but his counterplay comes just in time. White lacks a dark-squared bishop required for decisiveinfiltrati on while Black's e8-B makes sacrifices on f7 or g6 difficult. Purdy now unwound his position but White, probably believing he held the initiative, avoided simplification:} c5 $1 22. d5 (22. dxc5 {looks safer. (TDH)}) 22... Bd6 23. Qg5 {This prevents ...exd5 because of Nf5+ and may threaten R-d3 f3. Now Purdy finds a crucial defensive resource.} Nh7 $1 (23... Be7 $2 24. dxe6 {TDH}) 24. Qe3 (24. Nxh5+ {I suspect that most OTB players would have risked although the best reply to} Kh8 {is not entirely clear. With correct play, Black has a bishop for two or three not so strong pawns and White gets a lost position; very precise defence by Purdy. For example, if [see lines...] But abandoning the attack with 24 Qe3 just left Black with all the chances. (TDH) NB: Purdy doesn't give any analysis after Kh8.} 25. Qh6 $2 (25. Qf4 gxh5 26. Qh6 f6 27. Bxh7 Qxh7 28. Qxf6+ Qg7 29. Qxg7+ (29. Qxe6 $5) 29... Kxg7 30. dxe6 Bxe5 31. Rxd8 Rxd8 32. Rxe5 Kf6 33. Re2 Rd4 {and Black should win.}) 25... Bxe5 26. f4 Bxb2 27. Re2 Qb6 $1 $19 {or}) 24... Bxe5 25. Qxe5+ Qxe5 26. Rxe5 Nf6 27. Bc2 exd5 28. cxd5 Rd6 {Now Black clearly stands better.} 29. f3 Kf8 30. Ne2 b5 {Adjudicated won for Black} 0-1


