oved, and from now on the game hinges on Black's backward e-pawn. Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: 'Since ...e6 is now ruled out, the tremendous knight must be removed, and from now on the game hinges on Black's backward e-pawn.''} (20... Nd7 $5 {Purdy} 21. fxg6 hxg6 22. Bxd7 Qxd7 23. Rf3 f6 24. Raf1 e5 25. Qd2 Bxd5 26. Qxd5+ Kg7 $14 {Purdy: 'Myers' Myers}) 21. exd5 Qc7 22. Rad1 {Purdy: '!' '!' '!'} Rbd8 (22... Qc5 {Purdy: '!?' '!?' '!?'} 23. Qxc5 dxc5 24. d6 {Purdy: '!' '!' '!' with a winning endgame. i.e. Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: 'with a winning endgame. i.e.''} Rfe8 (24... exd6 {Purdy} 25. Rxd6 Rfd8 26. Rfd1 Rxd6 27. Rxd6 gxf5 28. Bxf5 a5 29. Bd3 c4 30. bxc4 Nxc4 31. Rd5 a4 32. Kf2 Rb6 33. g4 $14 {Purdy: 'Myers' Myers}) 25. dxe7 Rxe7 26. Rd6 {Purdy: '' '' '' threatening fxg6 followed by ff6. Purdy: 'Purdy Purdy/Salm: 'threatening fxg6 followed by ff6.''}) 23. Kh1 Nd7 (23... Qc5 {Purdy} 24. Qd2 Nd7 25. fxg6 hxg6 26. Bxd7 Rxd7) 24. fxg6 hxg6 25. Bxd7 Rxd7 26. Rf4 (26. Rd3 $5 {Purdy} Rdd8 27. Rg3 Rde8 28. h4 e5 29. Qe4 Kg7 30. h5 Qe7 {[%cal Yf8h8]} 31. Kg1 $1 (31. hxg6 $2 Rh8+ 32. Kg1 Qa7+ $132) 31... Rc8 32. Qg4 g5 33. Rgf3 Rc7 34. Rf5 $18 {Purdy: 'Myers' Myers}) 26... Qc5 27. Qd3 (27. Qd2 $5 {Purdy} Rc7 {Purdy} 28. c4 f6 29. Rg4 g5 30. Re1 $16 {Purdy: 'Myers' Myers}) 27... Qc8 (27... Rc7 $5 {Purdy}) 28. c4 (28. Rg4 $5 {Purdy}) 28... Rb7 (28... Rc7 $5 {Purdy}) 29. Rdf1 Kg7 30. R1f3 Qe8 {The way to win against a cramped game is not to attack but to prevent any worth-while freeing moves, while gradually edging your pieces into better positions until something just has to give. In a nutshell, watch the rat-holes. Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: 'The way to win against a cramped game is not to attack but to prevent any worth-while freeing moves, while gradually edging your pieces into better positions until something just has to give. In a nutshell, watch the rat-holes.''} 31. g4 (31. Kh2 $5 {Purdy}) 31... g5 (31... bxc4 $5 {Purdy} 32. Qc3+ Kg8 33. Rxc4 Rb5 34. Qd4 Qa8 35. Rc6 e6 36. Rxd6 Rxd5 37. Rxd5 exd5 $11 {Purdy: 'Myers' Myers}) 32. Qd4+ (32. Re4 $5 {Purdy}) 32... f6 {Purdy: '!' '!' '!'} 33. Re4 Rh8 (33... bxc4 $5 {Purdy}) 34. Rfe3 Qd8 35. b4 (35. Kg2 $5 {Purdy}) 35... bxc4 (35... Rc7 $5 {Purdy}) 36. Qxc4 Ra7 {Purdy: '?' '?' '?'} (36... e5 $1 {Purdy} 37. Qxa6 Qa8 38. Qxa8 Rxa8 39. a3 Rba7 40. b5 f5 41. Rb4 f4 $11 {Purdy: 'Myers' Myers}) 37. Qd4 Rc7 38. Qd3 Ra7 39. Kg2 {Purdy: '!' '!' '!'} Kf7 { (Salm) The Black e-pawn is not only backward but is also under a strong attack and is firmly prevented from advancing. The queen and the QR are tied down to it's defence, and the latter must also guard the a-pawn; the threat of h4 confines the KR in the corner. Black's forces are therefore not in a position to present a united front to any fresh aggression. Play proceeded: Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: ' (Salm) The Black e-pawn is not only backward but is also under a strong attack and is firmly prevented from advancing. The queen and the QR are tied down to it's defence, and the latter must also guard the a-pawn; the threat of h4 confines the KR in the corner. Black's forces are therefore not in a position to present a united front to any fresh aggression. Play proceeded:''} 40. Rc4 (40. a4 $5 {Purdy}) 40... Qb6 {(Salm) Threatens ...a5 Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: '(Salm) Threatens ...a5''} (40... Qb8 41. a4 Rd7 42. Qe4 Qb7 43. Rec3 Kg7 44. Qf5 $1 Kf7 {Purdy: '?' '?' '?'} (44... Rh4 $5 {Purdy}) 45. h4 $3 Rxh4 (45... gxh4 46. g5 $1 {Purdy: '+-!' '+-!' '+-!' Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: '!''}) 46. Qe6+ Kg7 47. Rc8 Rh8 48. Rxh8 Kxh8 49. Qf7 {and mate by h3. Purdy: '+-' '+-' '+-' Purdy: 'Purdy Purdy/Salm: 'and mate by h3.''}) 41. a4 Qb8 42. Qe4 {(Salm) A regrouping of forces - threat is 43.e6+ g7 44.ec3 to be followed by c8 and mates. Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: '(Salm) A regrouping of forces - threat is 43.e6+ g7 44.ec3 to be followed by c8 and mates.''} Kg7 43. Rec3 Rd7 {(Salm) Objective is a defence based on ...b7. Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: '(Salm) Objective is a defence based on ...b7.''} 44. h4 $3 {A pretty move which gives the game an artistic touch. A time comes when a cramped player has reached his maximum cramp and his opponent must attack at last. Black must take the pawn somehow. Purdy: 'Purdy/Salm: 'A pretty move which gives the game an artistic touch. A time comes when a cramped player has reached his maximum cramp and his opponent must attack at last. Black must take the pawn somehow.''} gxh4 {Purdy: '' '' ''} (44... Rxh4 {Purdy: '?' '?' '?'} 45. Rc8 Qb6 46. Re8 $18 {Purdy: 'Purdy' Purdy: 'Purdy'}) 45. g5 fxg5 {Purdy: '?' '?' '?'} (45... Rh5 $142 $5 {Purdy} 46. gxf6+ exf6 47. Qe6 Qd8 48. Rf3 Re5 49. Rg4+ Rg5 50. Kh3 Rb7 51. Rxh4 Qe7 52. Re3 Qxe6+ 53. dxe6 Re7 54. Rg4 Kh6 55. Kg3 f5 56. Rxg5 Kxg5 $11 {Purdy: 'Myers' Myers}) 46. Qf5 Qe8 47. Rc8 Qh5 (47... Rd8 48. Rxd8 Qxd8 49. Qxg5+ Kf7 50. Qf5+ Kg7 51. Rc4 $18 {Purdy: 'Purdy' Purdy: 'Purdy'}) 48. Rxh8 (48. Qxd7 $4 Qe2+ $11 {Purdy: 'Purdy' Purdy: 'Purdy'}) 48... Kxh8 49. Rc8+ Kg7 50. Qf8+ 1-0


