{How Purdy Won #38 has other notes. Purdy considered this was probably his best CC game ever.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 Ne4 7. Bxe7 Qxe7 8. cxd5 Nxc3 9. bxc3 exd5 10. Qb3 Qd6 11. c4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Nc6 13. Qc3 Bg4 $1 14. Nd2 (14. O-O Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rad8 16. Kh1 Qf6 17. Be2 Rfe8 18. Rae1 Rd7 19. Rg1 Ne7 $11) 14... Rad8 15. O-O Ne7 16. Rfc1 b6 17. Ne4 Qd7 18. Ng3 c6 19. Qa3 Ra8 {Thus far Guimard-Eliskases, Mar del Plata 1941, except one move less as Black had played ...h6.} 20. Rc2 Be6 21. Bxe6 Qxe6 22. Rac1 Rfd8 23. Ne2 Rd7 24. h3 g6 {} (24... h6 {is preferable, as this weakens the dark squares. But what a small weakness to work on, there being no bishops.}) 25. Nf4 Qd6 26. Qb2 {This is the start of a long combination.} Rc8 27. Nd3 c5 {A blow for freedom, but better to stay cramped rather than expose the .} 28. Ne5 Rdc7 29. dxc5 Qf6 {To prevent g4.} 30. Qd4 Nf5 31. Qf4 Qe6 32. Nd3 bxc5 33. Rxc5 Rxc5 34. Rxc5 Rxc5 35. Nxc5 Qxa2 {White is winning, although it does not look like it; but the combination is still in progress.} 36. Qb8+ Kg7 37. Nd7 Qa1+ 38. Kh2 Qa3 39. Qe5+ Kh6 {The conclusion of the 14-move combination. Black has difficulties but White had at first envisaged only 40 Qf4+ leading to a draw. He now finds the better line, using the  to block the  out.} 40. Nc5 $1 Qb4 {The final inaccuracy.} (40... f6 41. Qc7 $14 {is not such a clear win.}) 41. g4 f6 {The most difficult defence. Apparently White must content himself with the win of the a-pawn.} 42. Qc7 Ng7 43. Qxa7 Qb2 44. Nd3 Qc3 45. Qd7 f5 46. Qd6 Ne8 47. Qf8+ Ng7 48. gxf5 gxf5 (48... Qxd3 49. f6 {wins easily.}) 49. Qd6+ {Black resigned. If 49...h5 50 f4+ or if 49...g5 50 e7+. "A win spun from air" - Purdy} 1-0


