{How Purdy Won #1. Grandmaster C.J.S.Purdy (1906-1979) played in the 1937 (1st) & 1945 (1st) Australian Championships. Olympiad I preliminary, World Championship I semi-final and final, winning and thus becoming the 1st Correspondence World Champion in 1953. Editor of "ACR", "Check!" and "Chess World", was one of the world's greatest chess writers and teachers.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 Bxc3+ 5. Qxc3 Ne4 6. Qc2 f5 7. e3 {This game showed White that g3 was a better scheme.} b6 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. Ne2 Qh4 10. O-O Nc6 11. g3 Qf6 12. a3 $1 {White had thought to win a pawn at e4, hence his eleventh, but now decided that a subsequent ...Na5 would be fatal.} Ng5 13. f3 O-O 14. Bd2 Rae8 15. Bc3 Qh6 16. h4 $1 Nf7 17. e4 g5 18. Kg2 $3 {Permits 19.Rh1 in reply to 18...gxh4, but is dangerous, and only just turns out to be a sufficient defence.} g4 19. fxg4 Nce5 $3 {An imaginative surprise, with only one deeply hidden flaw.} 20. dxe5 fxe4 21. Bxe4 Qg6 22. Rf5 $3 (22. Rf4 {appeared to be the only line. After} Ng5 $3 23. hxg5 Rxf4 24. Nxf4 Bxe4+ 25. Kf2 Bxc2 26. Nxg6 hxg6 {Black has at least a draw and may win. So White decided on this counter-sacrifice.}) 22... Bxe4+ 23. Qxe4 exf5 24. gxf5 Nd6 25. Qd5+ Qf7 26. exd6 Rxe2+ 27. Kf3 Re6 28. g4 h5 {Black expected to win, although he had found it impossible to exchange queens without conceeding a supported passed pawn.} 29. dxc7 hxg4+ 30. Kxg4 Rc6 31. Rg1 $3 Kh7 32. Qxf7+ Rxf7 33. Re1 Rxc4+ 34. Kg5 Rc5 {But now, after White's 31st had forced his king out of play, is content to threaten perpetual check.} 35. Re5 Rg7+ 36. Kh5 Rc6 $1 {Has White blundered, permitting Rh6#?} 37. f6 $1 Rxf6 38. Rg5 Rh6+ 39. Kg4 Rxg5+ 40. Kxg5 Rc6 41. Be5 d5 {Prevents White winning by Bd6 but he finds another way, prettily sacrificing the h-pawn to divert the Black king.} 42. Kf5 b5 43. b4 a6 44. Kf4 Kg6 45. h5+ $1 Kxh5 46. Ke3 {And gets to d6 with a tempo to spare.} 1-0


