{How Purdy Won #43. The whole view of this game is changed by analysis published in Chess Mail during 1998.} 1. c4 {Purdy & others} Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bd3 e5 8. Ne2 d6 9. e4 Nh5 10. O-O g5 11. Bc2 Nf4 12. Ba4 Bd7 13. Ng3 cxd4 {CP: An aggressive scheme that Black was playing for and I was inviting. I had analysed it as leading to a game full of complexity favouring White. What I did not know was that it fitted in well with Black's imaginative and aggressive style. MN: Black's moves 13-15 were a suggestion from the magazine Ceskoslovensko Sach.} (13... Qf6 {Bronstein-Smyslov (Budapest 1950)}) 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. cxd4 Qf6 16. Be3 h5 $1 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. Rb1 Rd8 (18... h4 19. Nf5 Bxf5 20. exf5 Qxf5 $2 21. Qd6) 19. Qc2 h4 20. Nf5 Bxf5 21. exf5 O-O $1 22. Rfd1 Nh5 23. Bxa7 Ng7 24. a4 Nxf5 25. a5 $5 {White faced a question discussed by Tarrasch, whether to let a P come to h3 or stop it by h2-h3. He says to let it come and then play g3 is ''better for the endgame" but then makes his famous epigram "But between the opening and the endgame the gods have placed the middle-game" He concludes with the advice to play h3. Looking at this game objectively, I conclude that it bears out his advice. By defying it here, White gets a passed d-pawn rapidly to the seventh rank: but it does not outweigh the disruption of the castled position.} (25. h3 $5 {Purdy}) 25... h3 26. a6 Ra8 27. Bc5 Rfe8 28. a7 e4 $1 {Black's  and  are troublesome, and now the e8- is not entirely restricted to defence.} 29. Rb7 Nh4 {Threatening ...f3+.} 30. Qb3 Qf5 $1 31. Rdd7 $6 {Given a ! by both Purdy and Napolitano, but virtually refuted by Fritz5. CP: In playing this. I almost resigned myself to a draw. But Napolitano refrains from forcing the draw, as on all the positions as he knew them, It would have given me the title. [Napolitano didn't know Purdy had blundered against Mitchell.]} (31. Rb8 Qg4 32. g3 {where Purdy was worried about} e3 $1 (32... e3 {which indeed seems the best move, at least drawing for Black.} 33. Rxa8 Rxa8 34. Qb8+ Kh7)) 31... Nf3+ $4 {Sometimes designated !? but this was the blunder that decided the first CC World Championship! Strangely, the players seems to have had mutual blindness here and successive editors have until now only quoted from the players' notes. For example Napolitano, cited in Hanon Russell's book Correspondence Chess, analyses 31...Qc5 and says he should probably have played 31...e3. Apparently the mating combination, which computers now find quickly, was overlooked by the world's two strongest CC players of half a century ago. It is hard to imagine a Berliner or Umansky, even without using a computer, overlooking the refutation of 31 dd7; how standards have risen in the intervening years!} (31... Qxc5 32. Rxf7 e3 $1 (32... Qe5 33. Rfd7 $1 Qa1+ 34. Rd1 Rxa7 35. c5+ Kh8 36. Rbd7 $3 Qa3 37. Qf7 $18) 33. Qb2 exf2+ 34. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 35. Kxf2 $11 {Purdy}) (31... e3 $1 32. Qb2 (32. Rxf7 {also needs examination.}) 32... exf2+ 33. Qxf2 Qxf2+ {given as "= Purdy" in Tim Harding's official CC World Championships book but Fritz says White's winning, so what was drawing line?}) (31... hxg2 $3 $19 {(Purdy & others) Not mentioned in Purdy's notes but Fritz5 suggests Black is winning. } 32. Qb1 (32. Qg3 e3 $1 {Tim Runting suggested: 32...Nf3+ (32...Qxc5 33.Rxf7) 33.Kxg2 Qxc5 34.Rxf7 Qe5 (34...Qd4 35.Qc7) 35.Qxe5=} 33. Bxe3 (33. Rxf7 e2) 33... Rxa7 34. Bxa7 (34. Rxa7 Qb1+) 34... Re1#) (32. Rxf7 Nf3+ 33. Qxf3 (33. Kxg2 Qg4+ 34. Kf1 Qg1+ 35. Ke2 Qe1#) 33... exf3) (32. h3 Qxc5) (32. Qd1 $3 {Fritz and John Timm both think this is best. The whole of this variation is Timm's analysis.} Nf3+ 33. Kxg2 Nh4+ {(both Fritz and Hiarcs think this is best)} ({Black has various other ways of attacking, for example} 33... Qg4+ 34. Kf1 Nxh2+ 35. Ke1 Nf3+ 36. Kf1 Qh3+ 37. Ke2 Ne5 {but I cannot find a clear win for Black here either. In all cases the strong a7/b7 battery gives White substantial counterplay.}) 34. Kg3 $1 Qxc5 35. Rxf7 Qe5+ 36. Kg4 Qe6+ 37. Kxg5 $1 Nf3+ 38. Rxf3 exf3 39. Qd4 $1 Qe5+ 40. Qxe5 Rxe5+ { Both Fritz and Hiarcs think this position is won for Black, but according to John Timm, it's a clear positional draw because Black will never find an effective means of getting even one of his three pieces off the eighth rank. For example,} 41. Kf6 Re2 (41... Rae8 $2 {loses to} 42. Rb8) 42. Rb8+ Re8 43. Rb7 {Black is paralyzed, and White will make the bind even stronger by pushing the h-pawn up the board. The extra  is useless except for defence!}) 32... Qxc5 (32... Nf3+ 33. Kxg2 Qg4+ 34. Kf1 Nxh2+ 35. Ke1 Nf3+ 36. Kf1 Qh3+ 37. Ke2 Ne5) 33. Rxf7 Qe5 34. Rg7+ Qxg7 35. Rxg7+ Kxg7 36. Qb7+ Kg8 $19) 32. gxf3 exf3 33. Kf1 $1 {This was the move that Napolitano had underestimated.} (33. Be3 Rad8 34. Qd1 Qg4+ 35. Kf1 Qxc4+ $11 {Purdy}) 33... Qxc5 34. Qc3 $1 (34. Qxf3 $2 Qxc4+) (34. Rxf7 Re2) 34... Rf8 35. Qd3 $1 Qe5 $1 {Indirectly parrying the threat of Rxf7! and starting new devilment.} 36. Qxf3 Rae8 $1 37. Rb1 Qxh2 (37... Qe6 $1 {Napolitano}) 38. Rb3 (38. Qg3 $2 Qh1+ 39. Qg1 Qe4 $1 {40. Dg5:+ (P.)}) 38... Qe5 39. Qxh3 Qf4 {! Purdy but ? Nap.} (39... Qe2+ 40. Kg2 Re4 41. Rg3 g4 {Napolitano} (41... g4 {with some hope of drawing by perpetual (N) but} 42. Qh5 {wins easily, e.g.} Re6 43. Rxf7 Qe4+ 44. Kh2 Rxf7 45. a8=Q+)) {Purdy: I wrote out analysis for 20 possible 40th moves. At first I could not make any of them win. Finally I found a curious one.} 40. c5 $3 Qc4+ (40... Qc1+ 41. Kg2 Re1 42. Qf3 $1 Rh1 43. Qxf7+ $1 Rxf7 44. a8=Q+ Kg7 (44... Rf8 $2 45. Qxf8+ $1 Kxf8 46. Rb8#) 45. Rxf7+) 41. Kg2 Re4 ({The curious win was by} 41... Qxc5 42. Qh6 {Threat h3} g4 43. Rg3 Re4 44. Qh4 Qf5 45. Rd8 $18) 42. Qf5 $1 Qxb3 43. Qxe4 Kg7 44. Qf5 g4 45. Qxg4+ {A wild game. In CC a simple style won't win a world title.} (45. Qxg4+ {If} Kh7 46. Rd1 {mates or gets  for .}) 1-0


