{How Purdy Won #28} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bb6 5. a4 a6 6. Ba3 {Ulvestad (Chess Charts, 1940)} d6 (6... Nf6 7. b5 (7. Nc3 {also playable (Harding & Cafferty)}) 7... Na5 8. Nxe5 d5 {"is all far from clear" - Larry Evans}) 7. b5 axb5 (7... Na5 8. Be2 {8 Nxe5 is hopelessly unsound} Be6 {retaining a-pawns (Purdy)}) 8. axb5 Nd4 (8... Na5 9. Be2 Be6 10. d3 Qd7 11. Nc3 Ne7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bb4 c5 14. Ba3 f6 15. Qe1 d5 16. Na4 {Not possible with a-pawn still here (the point of Purdy's move 7 idea)} Qxb5 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. d4 $16 {Ulvestad}) 9. Nxd4 Bxd4 10. c3 Bb6 $5 (10... Bc5 11. O-O {threat d4} (11. d4 $2 exd4 12. cxd4 Bb4+ $17 {Ulvestad})) 11. O-O Qf6 12. Kh1 Nh6 13. f3 O-O 14. d3 Bd7 15. Nd2 Kh8 16. Qe2 g5 $6 (16... Qe7 {Muir-Frantzen}) 17. Ra2 Ng8 18. d4 $1 $16 Ne7 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. Rfa1 Rad8 21. Nf1 Rg8 22. Ne3 Bxe3 23. Qxe3 Nc8 24. Qc5 Be6 25. Qxc7 Rd7 26. Qc5 b6 27. Qb4 g4 28. fxg4 Rxg4 29. h3 Rg8 30. Rf1 Qxf1+ 31. Bxf1 Bxa2 32. c4 Rd1 33. Kg1 f6 34. c5 Rb1 35. Qc3 Rb3 36. Qc1 Rg7 37. cxb6 Nxb6 38. Bf8 Rf7 39. Bh6 1-0


