{How Purdy Won #24} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. d4 d5 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. O-O Be7 8. c4 Bg4 9. cxd5 Qxd5 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxf3 $2 (11... O-O 12. Bf4 $140 Bd6 $11) 12. Qxf3 Qxf3 13. gxf3 O-O (13... O-O-O $14 {Tarrasch-Marshall, Ostend 1905}) 14. Rb1 Rab8 15. Re1 Bd6 16. f4 f5 17. Bd2 Ne7 18. Kg2 b6 19. Re6 Kh8 20. Kf3 Rbd8 21. Rbe1 Ng8 22. c4 Nf6 23. Bc2 Nh5 24. Be3 $1 g6 25. c5 $3 {Illustrating Purdy's maxim "Always look for a way of ignoring the threat".} Ng7 26. cxd6 Nxe6 27. d5 Ng7 28. Bd4 Rf7 29. Re7 {At this point Purdy, under the false impression that the game was about to be adjudicated, sent a long string of conditionals and his opponent resigned.} (29. Re7 Rxe7 (29... Kg8 30. dxc7) (29... Rdf8 30. Rxc7 b5 31. d7 Rd8 32. d6 Rfxd7 33. Bb3 $1) 30. dxe7 Re8 31. Bf6 h6 32. d6 cxd6 33. Bb3 Kh7 34. Bf7 b5 35. Ke3 a5 36. Kd4 b4 37. Kd5 Nh5 38. Ke6) 1-0


