{How Purdy Won #23} 1. e4 {The official result of this game was a draw as slow progress meant that at one point all open Australian games were agreed drawn so that the event could proceed to the final (information Erik Larsson). This circumstance is not mentioned in the book, where fuller notes can be found, but was clarified in 1998 in correspondence between E.L,. T.H. and Alvaro Pereira of Portugal. Purdy continued this game as a friendly and eventually lost, but he once said he would probably have drawn had it still counted in the team event (see move 20).} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Qf3 cxb5 9. Qxa8 Bc5 10. b4 Bxb4 11. O-O O-O 12. Nc3 Nh5 13. h4 $6 Nb7 14. Qxa7 Ng3 15. Nxb5 Bc5 16. Qa4 h6 17. d4 $1 Ne2+ $1 18. Kh1 exd4 19. Nf3 Re8 20. Bd2 $2 (20. Re1 {idea Rxe2 should draw.}) 20... Re4 21. g3 Qd7 22. Rae1 Qh3+ 23. Nh2 Bg4 24. Qb3 Be6 25. Qd3 Bd5 26. f3 Nxg3+ 27. Kg1 Nxf1 (27... Nxf1 28. fxe4 Qxh2+ 29. Kxf1 Be6) 0-1


