{How Purdy Won #20; cf Purdy article in CHESS April 1976} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 Bg7 5. e3 c5 6. dxc5 Qa5 7. cxd5 $6 (7. Rc1) 7... Nxd5 {Purdy offered the rest of the game as a conditional but later found a win.} 8. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Qxc3+ 10. Ke2 Qxa1 11. Be5 Qc1 $6 {Purdy later improved on some Russian analysis to find a win for Black here:} (11... Qb1 $1 12. Bxh8 Be6 13. Qd3 $8 Qxa2+ 14. Kf3 $1 f6 15. Bg7 {and now} Nd7 $1 $19 {Purdy, improving on old Russian analysis which only considered 15...Nc6.  (TH: Is this true? Maybe White is better?)} 16. Qd4 $140 Rd8 17. Kg3 Qa5 {for details see Purdy analysis in quoted sources}) 12. Bxh8 Be6 $1 13. Qxb7 Qc2+ {This game has been repeated in some OTB master tournaments, e.g. Filip-Pachman, Bucharest 1954, and both Darga-Pachman and Berger-Bilek in the 1964 Amsterdam interzonal. See BCM 1964 pp329-30 but not discussing the possibility 11...Qb1.} 1/2-1/2


