{How Purdy Won #6. Dr Cornforth was later a Nobel prize winner for Chemistry.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c6 $1 {Perhaps Cornforth was counting on the "book" line 7...b6 followed by ...c5 as in Rubinstein,A-Steiner,A/Budapest 1929. It leads to "hanging pawns". The point of playing 7...c6 at once is that it enable Black to play ...Bd6 if hit by a3, as Nb5 is prevented.} 8. Nge2 $1 {More elastic than 8.Nf3.} Re8 9. Bd2 Nbd7 10. Ng3 Nf8 11. O-O a6 $1 12. Na4 {Had White seen deeper, he would have played Rfc1! first.} Bd6 13. Rfc1 Ng4 14. Be1 $2 {Overlooking Black's fifteenth, apparently.} (14. Nf1 $8 Qh4 15. g3 Qf6 {still leaves Black with a good attack.}) ({Of course not} 14. h3 $2 Nxf2 $19) 14... Qh4 15. h3 Nxe3 16. Qd2 (16. Qe2 Qxd4 $19) 16... Nxg2 17. Kxg2 ({If} 17. Nb6 Nf4 $1 18. Nxa8 Nxh3+ 19. Kf1 Nf4 20. Kg1 N8e6 $19) 17... Bxh3+ {The attack is overwhelming.} (17... Bxh3+ 18. Kg1 (18. Kh1 Bf4 $1 19. Qb4 Ne6 $1 20. Bd2 Ng5 21. Bxf4 Bg4+ 22. Kg2 Qh3+ 23. Kg1 Nf3#) 18... Ne6 $1) 0-1


