{How Purdy Won #14} 1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Be2 f5 {Alekine's suggestion (but never played) as a result of Tartakower's use of 3.Be2 in the New York 1924 tournament in which he scored 2.5/1.5.} 4. exf5 (4. e5 d6 5. d4 {Tartakower} dxe5 6. dxe5 Qxd1+ 7. Bxd1 Be6 8. Bxf4 (8. Nf3 Nd7 9. Ng5 Ke7 $1 10. Bxf4 h6) 8... Nd7 9. Nf3 O-O-O {and in either case, White's pawn on e5 becomes a fixed weaknesss.}) 4... Qh4+ 5. Kf1 d5 6. Nc3 (6. Bh5+ Kd8 $1 {Alekhine.}) 6... c6 7. d4 Bd6 8. Bd3 Ne7 9. Qe2 O-O (9... Qf6 $142 10. Nf3 h6 11. g4 $140 fxg3 12. hxg3 O-O 13. g4 Bxf5 $1 $19 {Bologan}) 10. Nf3 Qf6 11. g4 fxg3 12. Bg5 Qf7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qxe7 Bxe7 15. Re1 Bd6 16. Kg2 gxh2 17. Nh4 Nd7 18. Ne2 Nf6 19. Ng3 Ng4 20. Rhf1 Bd7 21. Kh3 h1=Q+ $1 22. Nxh1 Nh6 23. Kg2 Rf7 24. Re5 Re7 $3 25. f6 Bxe5 26. fxe7 Bxd4 27. Rf8+ Rxf8 28. Bxh7+ Kf7 29. exf8=Q+ Kxf8 {The book doesn't give the continuation:} 30. c3 Bf6 31. Ng6+ Kf7 32. Nf2 Bf5 33. Nh8+ Ke6 34. Ng6 Kd6 35. Kf3 Bb1 36. a3 Kc5 37. Ke2 Bf5 38. Nf8 Kc4 39. Bxf5 Nxf5 40. Kd2 Kb3 41. Kc1 d4 42. cxd4 Bxd4 43. Nd3 g5 44. Ne6 g4 {BLACK TREE: '0-1 (44) Crowl,F-Purdy,C corr CCLA 1945 UltraCorr3a [Purdy]'} 0-1


